<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-linear-transformations">
  <title>Linear Transformations</title>

  <p>What makes a transformation a matrix transformation?</p>

  <definition xml:id="def-2-4-linear-transformation">
    <title>Linear Transformations</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A transformation <m>T:\R^n\to\R^m</m> is a <term>linear transformation</term> if
        <ol>
          <li><m>T(\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{y}) = T(\mathbf{x}) + T(\mathbf{y})</m> for every <m>\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{y} \in \R^n</m>.</li>
          <li><m>T(c\mathbf{x})=cT(\mathbf{x})</m> for every <m>\mathbf{x} \in \R^n</m> and <m>c \in \R</m>.</li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <activity>
    <title>Verifying Linear Transformations</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Identifying <m>\R</m> with <m>\R^1</m>, show that <m>T(x)=2x</m> is a linear transformation, while <m>T(x)=x^2</m> is not.</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        For <m>T(x)=2x</m>:
        <me> T(x+y) = 2(x+y) = 2x + 2y = T(x) + T(y) </me>
        and
        <me>T(cx) = 2(cx) = c(2x) = cT(x)</me>
        Therefore <m>T(x)=2x</m> is a linear transformation.
      </p>

      <p>
        For <m>T(x)=x^2</m>:
        <me> T(x+y) = (x+y)^2 = x^2 + 2xy + y^2 </me>
        and
        <me> T(x) + T(y) = x^2 + y^2</me>
        but it is not always true (and in fact, is almost never true) that
        <me>x^2 + 2xy + y^2 = x^2 + y^2</me>. 
        So it is not always true that <m>T(x + y) = T(x) + T(y)</m>, and so <m>T(x)=x^2</m> is not a linear transformation.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </activity>

  <activity>
    <title>Properties of Linear Transformations</title>
    <introduction>
      Suppose <m>T</m> is a linear transformation.
    </introduction>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find <m>T(\mathbf{0})</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Since <m>\mathbf{0} = 0 \mathbf{0}</m>,
          <me>T(\mathbf{0}) = T(0\mathbf{0}) = 0T(\mathbf{0})</me>,
          so <m>T(\mathbf{0}) = \mathbf{0}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>T(-\mathbf{x})</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <me>T(-\mathbf{x}) = T((-1)\mathbf{x}) = (-1)T(\mathbf{x}) = -T(\mathbf{x})</me>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </activity>

  <p>
    Recall the notion of a linear combination from <xref ref="def-1-3-column-vectors"/>, i.e. that a vector <m>\mathbf{y}\in\R^n</m> is a <term>linear combination</term> of vectors <m>\mathbf{x}_1, \mathbf{x}_2,\ldots \mathbf{x}_k</m> if there are scalars <m>a_1, a_2, \ldots, a_k</m> such that
    <me>\mathbf{y}=a_1\mathbf{x}_1+a_2\mathbf{x}_2+\cdots a_k\mathbf{x}_k.</me>
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-2-4-linear-combination-transform">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>T:\R^n\to\R^m</m> is a linear transformation, then
      </p>
      <me>T(a_1\mathbf{x}_1+a_2\mathbf{x}_2+\cdots a_k\mathbf{x}_k)= a_1T(\mathbf{x}_1) + a_2T(\mathbf{x}_2) + \cdots + a_kT(\mathbf{x}_k)</me>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  <activity>
    <title>Finding Images Under Linear Transformations</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>T:\R^2\to\R^3</m> is a linear transformation with 
        <me>T((1,2)) = (-1,0,3)</me>
        and
        <me>T((-1,0)) = (4,1,2)</me>.
        Find
        <me>T((3,4))</me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We plan to use <xref ref="thm-2-4-linear-combination-transform"/>. To do this, we need to write the vector <m>(3,4)</m> as a linear combination of <m>(1,2)</m> and <m>(-1,0)</m>.
      </p>
      
      <p>Let <m>a,b</m> be scalars such that:
      <me>\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} = a\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} + b\begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</me>
      In order for this equation to hold, the scalars <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> must satisfy the system of linear equations:
      <md>
        <mrow>a - b = 3</mrow>
        <mrow>2a = 4</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      From the second equation: <m>a = 2</m>
    </p>
    <p>Substituting into the first equation: <m>2 - b = 3</m>, so <m>b = -1</m>.</p>

    <p>Therefore,
      <me>(3,4) = 2 (1,2) - (-1,0)</me>.
      By the linearity of <m>T</m> and <xref ref="thm-2-4-linear-combination-transform"/>,
      <md>
        <mrow>T((3,4)) \amp = 2 T((1,2)) - T((-1,0))
        </mrow>
        <mrow> &amp;= 2 (-1,0,3) - (4,1,2)</mrow>
        <mrow>&amp;= \begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ 0 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
        <mrow>&amp;= \begin{bmatrix} -6 \\ -1 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  </solution>
</activity>


<theorem xml:id="thm-linear-transformation-matrix">
  <statement>
    <p>Let <m>T:\R^n\to\R^m</m> be a transformation.</p>
    <ol>
      <li><m>T</m> is a linear transformation if and only if it is a matrix transformation.</li>
      <li>In this case, <m>T=T_A</m> is the matrix transformation induced by the unique matrix <m>A</m>, given in terms of its columns by</li>
    </ol>
    <me>A=\begin{bmatrix} T(\mathbf{e}_1) &amp; T(\mathbf{e}_2) &amp; \cdots &amp; T(\mathbf{e}_n) \end{bmatrix},</me>
    <p>where <m>\mathbf{e}_1,\mathbf{e}_2, \ldots \mathbf{e}_n</m> are the standard basis vectors of <m>\R^n</m>.</p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>First, we show that if <m>T</m> is a matrix transformation, then it is linear. If <m>T = T_A</m> for a matrix <m>A</m>, then the distributive properties from <xref ref="thm-2-2-distributive-properties"/> show that:
    <me>
      T(\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{y}) = A(\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{y}) = A\mathbf{x} + A\mathbf{y} = T(\mathbf{x}) + T(\mathbf{y})
    </me>
    and
    <me>
      T(c\mathbf{x}) = A(c\mathbf{x}) = cA\mathbf{x} = cT(\mathbf{x})
    </me>
    By <xref ref="def-2-4-linear-transformation"/>, this shows <m>T_A</m> is linear.
  </p>

  <p>
    Now we show that if <m>T</m> is any linear transformation, then it is a matrix transformation. Define a matrix
    <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} T(\mathbf{e}_1) &amp; T(\mathbf{e}_2) &amp; \cdots &amp; T(\mathbf{e}_n) \end{bmatrix}</me>.
    For any
    <me>\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \\ \vdots \\ x_n \end{bmatrix}</me>,
    we can write:
    <me>
      \mathbf{x} = x_1\mathbf{e}_1 + x_2\mathbf{e}_2 + \cdots + x_n\mathbf{e}_n
    </me>
    By linearity,
    <md>
      <mrow>T(\mathbf{x}) &amp;= T(x_1\mathbf{e}_1 + x_2\mathbf{e}_2 + \cdots + x_n\mathbf{e}_n)</mrow>
      <mrow>&amp;= x_1T(\mathbf{e}_1) + x_2T(\mathbf{e}_2) + \cdots + x_nT(\mathbf{e}_n)</mrow>
      <mrow>&amp;= A\mathbf{x}</mrow>
    </md>
    Therefore <m>T = T_A</m> is a matrix transformation.
  </p>

  <p>
    To show that a linear transformation is a matrix transformation for a unique matrix <m>A</m>, suppose <m>T = T_B</m> for some other matrix <m>B</m>. Then it would be true that <m>T_A \mathbf{e}_j = T_B \mathbf{e}_j</m> for each standard basis vector <m>\mathbf{e}_j</m>. But (recall <xref ref="fact-2-2-standard-basis"/>) <m>T_A \mathbf{e}_j = A\mathbf{e}_j</m> is the <m>j</m>th column of <m>A</m>, and <m>T_B \mathbf{e}_j = B\mathbf{e}_j</m> is the <m>j</m>th column of <m>B</m>. Therefore the columns of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are identical, so <m>A = B</m>.
  </p>
</proof>
</theorem>

<corollary>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>T:\R^k\to\R^n</m>, and <m>S:\R^n\to\R^m</m> are linear transformations, then <m>S\circ T</m> is a linear transformation.
    </p>
  </statement>
</corollary>

<activity>
  <title>Finding Matrix Representation</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>Define <m>T:\R^2\to\R^3</m> by</p>
    <me>T\left(\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix}\right)=\begin{bmatrix} x_1 +x_2 \\ x_1 \\ 3x_2 \end{bmatrix}</me>
  </introduction>

  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show <m>T</m> is a linear transformation.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        Let's verify both properties of linear transformations:
        <md>
          <mrow>T(\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{y}) &amp;= \begin{bmatrix} (x_1+y_1)+(x_2+y_2) \\ x_1+y_1 \\ 3(x_2+y_2) \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
          <mrow>&amp;= \begin{bmatrix} x_1+x_2 \\ x_1 \\ 3x_2 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} y_1+y_2 \\ y_1 \\ 3y_2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
          <mrow>&amp;= T(\mathbf{x}) + T(\mathbf{y})</mrow>
        </md>
        and
        <md>
          <mrow>T(c\mathbf{x}) &amp;= \begin{bmatrix} cx_1+cx_2 \\ cx_1 \\ 3cx_2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
          <mrow>&amp;= c\begin{bmatrix} x_1+x_2 \\ x_1 \\ 3x_2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
          <mrow>&amp;= cT(\mathbf{x})</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>

  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find <m>A</m>, where <m>T = T_A</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        To find <m>A</m>, we need <m>T(\mathbf{e}_1)</m> and <m>T(\mathbf{e}_2)</m>:
        <md>
          <mrow>T(\mathbf{e}_1) &amp;= T\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
          <mrow>T(\mathbf{e}_2) &amp;= T\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
        </md>
        Therefore:
        <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} T\mathbf{e}_1 \amp T\mathbf{e}_2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix}</me>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>

  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Is there an <m>\mathbf{x}</m> in <m>\R^2</m> with <m>T(\mathbf{x})=\begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ -1 \\ 6\end{bmatrix}</m>?
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        We need to solve the equation
        <me>A\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ -1 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix}</me>. 
        This gives the system
        <me>
          \begin{array}{cccccc}
          x_1 \amp + \amp x_2 \amp = \amp 4\\
          x_1 \amp   \amp     \amp = \amp -1\\
          \amp   \amp 3x_2 \amp = \amp 6
          \end{array}
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>From second equation: <m>x_1 = -1</m></p>
      <p>From third equation: <m>x_2 = 2</m></p>
      <p>If <m>x_1 = -1</m> and <m>x_2 = 2</m>, the first equation reads <m>-1 + 2 = 4</m>, which is never true. So the system has no solution, and so there is no such <m>\mathbf{x}</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</task>
</activity>




</section>